  "prompt": "How did Benchling get started?",
  "response": "Benchling was founded in 2012 by Saji Wickramasekara and Ashu Singhal, who were both graduate students in bioengineering at Stanford University at the time. They recognized that scientific research, particularly in biology and life sciences, was hindered by inefficient data management and collaboration tools.\n\nThe founders saw that many researchers were still using outdated tools like spreadsheets and paper notebooks to track their experiments and data, which made collaboration and data analysis difficult. Their vision was to create a modern, cloud-based platform specifically designed for life science research that could help scientists manage, analyze, and share their research more effectively.\n\nInitially, Benchling started as a free tool for academic researchers, offering features like electronic lab notebooks, sequence management, and collaboration capabilities. As the platform gained popularity among researchers, they gradually expanded their offerings and began serving pharmaceutical and biotechnology companies.\n\nThe company has since grown significantly, raising venture capital funding and becoming a widely used platform in the life sciences research community. Today, Benchling provides research and development software for biologics, gene therapy, cell and gene editing, and other advanced scientific research domains.",
